instructions:
## Set up TanStack Query (React Query) v5

### 1. Install dependencies
- Install TanStack Query and its DevTools:
  ```
  npm install @tanstack/react-query
  npm install -D @tanstack/react-query-devtools
  ```
- Do NOT install `react-query` (v3/v4 package) — the current package is `@tanstack/react-query`.

### 2. Create a QueryClient provider wrapper
- TanStack Query requires a client-side `QueryClientProvider`. In Next.js App Router, create a wrapper component:
  Create `app/providers.tsx`:
  ```tsx
  'use client';

  import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider } from '@tanstack/react-query';
  import { ReactQueryDevtools } from '@tanstack/react-query-devtools';
  import { useState } from 'react';

  export function Providers({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
    const [queryClient] = useState(
      () =>
        new QueryClient({
          defaultOptions: {
            queries: {
              staleTime: 60 * 1000, // 1 minute
            },
          },
        })
    );

    return (
      <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
        {children}
        <ReactQueryDevtools initialIsOpen={false} />
      </QueryClientProvider>
    );
  }
  ```
- Use `useState` (not a module-level variable) to create the QueryClient — this prevents shared state across requests in SSR.

### 3. Wrap the root layout
- Update `app/layout.tsx` to use the Providers wrapper:
  ```tsx
  import { Providers } from './providers';

  export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
    return (
      <html lang="en">
        <body>
          <Providers>{children}</Providers>
        </body>
      </html>
    );
  }
  ```

### 4. Create typed API functions
- Keep API calls separate from query hooks (`lib/api/posts.ts`):
  ```ts
  export type Post = {
    id: number;
    title: string;
    body: string;
    userId: number;
  };

  export async function fetchPosts(): Promise<Post[]> {
    const res = await fetch('/api/posts');
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch posts');
    return res.json();
  }

  export async function fetchPost(id: number): Promise<Post> {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/posts/${id}`);
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`Failed to fetch post ${id}`);
    return res.json();
  }

  export async function createPost(data: Omit<Post, 'id'>): Promise<Post> {
    const res = await fetch('/api/posts', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify(data),
    });
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to create post');
    return res.json();
  }
  ```

### 5. Create query key factories
- Define query keys in one place to avoid typos and enable targeted invalidation:
  ```ts
  // lib/api/query-keys.ts
  export const postKeys = {
    all: ['posts'] as const,
    lists: () => [...postKeys.all, 'list'] as const,
    list: (filters: string) => [...postKeys.lists(), { filters }] as const,
    details: () => [...postKeys.all, 'detail'] as const,
    detail: (id: number) => [...postKeys.details(), id] as const,
  };
  ```

### 6. Implement useQuery in a component
- Create a client component that fetches data:
  ```tsx
  'use client';

  import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query';
  import { fetchPosts, postKeys } from '@/lib/api/posts';

  export function PostsList() {
    const { data: posts, isPending, isError, error } = useQuery({
      queryKey: postKeys.lists(),
      queryFn: fetchPosts,
    });

    if (isPending) return <div>Loading...</div>;
    if (isError) return <div>Error: {error.message}</div>;

    return (
      <ul>
        {posts.map((post) => (
          <li key={post.id}>{post.title}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    );
  }
  ```
- In v5, use `isPending` instead of `isLoading` for the loading state.

### 7. Implement useMutation
- Add a mutation for creating data:
  ```tsx
  'use client';

  import { useMutation, useQueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';
  import { createPost, postKeys } from '@/lib/api/posts';

  export function CreatePostForm() {
    const queryClient = useQueryClient();

    const mutation = useMutation({
      mutationFn: createPost,
      onSuccess: () => {
        // Invalidate and refetch the posts list
        queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: postKeys.lists() });
      },
    });

    const handleSubmit = (e: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) => {
      e.preventDefault();
      const form = e.currentTarget;
      mutation.mutate({
        title: form.title.value,
        body: form.body.value,
        userId: 1,
      });
    };

    return (
      <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
        <input name="title" placeholder="Title" required />
        <textarea name="body" placeholder="Body" required />
        <button type="submit" disabled={mutation.isPending}>
          {mutation.isPending ? 'Creating...' : 'Create'}
        </button>
        {mutation.isError && <p>Error: {mutation.error.message}</p>}
      </form>
    );
  }
  ```

### 8. Prefetching in Server Components (optional)
- For SSR/SSG with App Router, prefetch data in a Server Component and dehydrate it:
  Add `npm install @tanstack/react-query` server-side helpers are built-in. Update `app/providers.tsx` to accept `dehydratedState`:
  ```tsx
  // In a Server Component page:
  import { dehydrate, HydrationBoundary, QueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';
  import { fetchPosts } from '@/lib/api/posts';
  import { PostsList } from '@/components/posts-list';
  import { postKeys } from '@/lib/api/query-keys';

  export default async function PostsPage() {
    const queryClient = new QueryClient();
    await queryClient.prefetchQuery({
      queryKey: postKeys.lists(),
      queryFn: fetchPosts,
    });

    return (
      <HydrationBoundary state={dehydrate(queryClient)}>
        <PostsList />
      </HydrationBoundary>
    );
  }
  ```
- This pattern renders the initial HTML with data and hydrates on the client without a loading flash.

### Common Errors
- **`No QueryClient set, use QueryClientProvider`** → The component using `useQuery` is not inside `QueryClientProvider`. Check that `Providers` wraps the component in the layout and has `'use client'`.
- **`isLoading` always true** → In v5, `isLoading` was renamed to `isPending` for queries. Replace `isLoading` with `isPending`.
- **Shared QueryClient across requests (SSR data leak)** → Never create the QueryClient outside a component or `useState`. Always use `useState(() => new QueryClient())` in the provider.
- **Stale data not refreshing** → `staleTime` is set too high. Reduce it, or call `queryClient.invalidateQueries()` after a mutation.
- **`useQuery` fires on every render** → The `queryKey` array is being recreated each render (e.g., using an inline object). Define stable query keys using a key factory.
- **TypeScript error on `data`** → Provide a type to `useQuery<PostType>()` or ensure the `queryFn` return type is inferred.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT create `QueryClient` outside a component (e.g., `const queryClient = new QueryClient()` at module level) — it leaks state between SSR requests.
- Do NOT use `useQuery` in a Server Component — it requires a client context. Add `'use client'` to components that call hooks.
- Do NOT manually `fetch` in a `useEffect` alongside TanStack Query — let TanStack Query manage the lifecycle.
- Do NOT put sensitive secrets in `queryFn` that runs on the client — all client-side queries are visible in the browser.
- Do NOT forget to call `queryClient.invalidateQueries()` after mutations that change server data — stale cache will show outdated UI.
- Do NOT nest `QueryClientProvider` — having multiple providers can cause unexpected cache isolation.
- Do NOT use string query keys (`queryKey: 'posts'`) — always use arrays (`queryKey: ['posts']`) for proper cache key scoping.
